<subSubSection id="738821A997DE4CED101837D2CB1AB259" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D63A8D1CB6AA7C90ED58E156E24940E7" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="94823D6ED22EF2EA70BCE75B2A3790BB" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="367152AEF997EF10193A5378A4736106" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="1843838FA9CAF325E718283EAE570DA9" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="6034FC870458C50395E504AD62E14A53" class="Arachnida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Tara" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tara" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E93DCA5E30D25B6E3DE0E129B3DA2CD1" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Tara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2EB3EA97743A903CD8BCB9EFD32C4525" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. A-D Phylogeny of the Caesalpinia group. Bayesian phylogram based on 312 accessions, including only accessions with two or more loci. Branch support values are indicated as follows: branches in bold indicate that maximum support has been attained in the MP, ML and Bayesian phylogenetic analyses; otherwise, posterior probabilities are indicated above in bold, with bootstrap support from ML analyses (italicised) and parsimony analyses separated by a slash below the branches; for each terminal, the species name is followed by the collector number of the corresponding voucher (see Appendix 1 for full voucher details); the suffix ** indicates that several sequences from different accessions of the same species were concatenated for analysis (see Appendix 1 for details); for major clades and genera, the names used by Gagnon et al. (2013) are indicated, as well as the corresponding new genera." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.71.9203.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/106276" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">3</figureCitation>
), but differs in having flowers with a lower cucullate sepal with an entire margin (vs. a lower cucullate sepal with a pectinate margin), and dehiscent, coriaceous, laterally compressed pods (except for 
<taxonomicName id="B7718C424D2D6E45E557A029F06DA575" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum madagascariense" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="madagascariense">
<emphasis id="35672CB3D7569BFACC50C194E927BBFD" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum madagascariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which has inflated fruits) (vs. indehiscent, somewhat fleshy, coriaceous pods that are slightly turgid). Morphologically, species of 
<taxonomicName id="276EC66EB95B94A52609187F0A498925" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="ADA65B7F464421DFAC9C7793D5663416" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most likely to be confused with those of 
<taxonomicName id="59A1521925EF5171293DF0C4736A152B" authorityName="L. Sp. Pl. 1: 380" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Caesalpinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Caesalpinia" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A5CC7A8F11CA1C809C806C0B4950A8E8" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Caesalpinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.s., but no reliable diagnostic characters have been found to differentiate these two genera. The corolla of 
<taxonomicName id="30FD796755BC9822B1AD294368FFC18A" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2ED6500D6098B75FB05F2668A80FD044" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species is consistently yellow and the flowers are bee pollinated, whereas 
<taxonomicName id="36B77D61C6ADAEE7F979E42E7E6152E3" authorityName="L. Sp. Pl. 1: 380" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Caesalpinia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Caesalpinia" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="03D8AFE0E54CD4577994FE50F476CDE5" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Caesalpinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.s. species display a wide range of flower colour (yellow, orange, red, green and white) and pollination syndromes (chiropterophily, ornitophily, psychophily and mellitophily).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
