<subSubSection id="8295EB39AC0EF468CE98526B4E3D8006" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph id="6446732517C1806E95B1EA3D81655923" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Emended description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A690E506C05BA168C4165F3FEA6AAA85" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
Shrubs to small trees, 0.5-2 (-5) m tall, armed with straight or curved, deflexed prickles, scattered along shoots and also in pairs at the petiole base (except 
<taxonomicName id="F4C7A48E2B5C142197E1E104389CA714" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum madagascariense" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="madagascariense">
<emphasis id="3A2EFE9AB37AE21C96CD33FFC67CFADF" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum madagascariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is unarmed); young twigs glabrous to pubescent, eglandular. Stipules either minute or foliaceous and conspicuous, caducous (persistent in 
<taxonomicName id="673DE7200EFF73ACBE4A5F58433B5ACC" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="E. Gagnon &amp; G. P. Lewis" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="E. Gagnon &amp; G. P. Lewis" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum stuckertii" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stuckertii">
<emphasis id="1CF3DB83C01AE9C64F79A52F7B3857AC" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum stuckertii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Leaves alternate, bipinnate, ending with a pair of pinnae; petiole and rachis glabrous and eglandular, with membranous or spinulose stipels at the insertions of pinnae on the leaf rachis, occasionally also at the insertion of the leaflets on the pinnae; pinnae opposite, in 1-6 pairs per leaf; leaflets opposite, in 2-10 (-11) pairs per pinna, elliptic, obovate to orbicular, with a rounded, acuminate or emarginate apex, c. 2-25 
<normalizedToken id="3B627DE06F98FB75BC96A8EE30CA9E7F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-12 mm, leaflet blades glabrous to pubescent, eglandular. Inflorescence a terminal or axillary raceme; bracts caducous (acuminate and filiform in 
<taxonomicName id="6B52DAA3A721D022CEEE8A4828B64A1F" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="E. Gagnon &amp; G. P. Lewis" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="E. Gagnon &amp; G. P. Lewis" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum stuckertii" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="stuckertii">
<emphasis id="23530680BF81D3211FA1D405CCFFE922" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum stuckertii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Flowers bisexual, zygomorphic; calyx a short hypanthium with 5 sepals, c. 4-10 mm long, eglandular, glabrous to finely pubescent, lower sepal cucullate and covering the other 4 sepals in bud, all sepals caducous, leaving a persistent free hypanthium ring on the pedicel as the fruit develops; petals 5, free, yellow, the median petal sometimes with red markings on the inner face of the blade, c. 5-10 mm long, obovate, petal claw almost absent (present in 
<taxonomicName id="64F2CE72AEEB5946CD97219AA265D26D" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum madagascariense" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="madagascariense">
<emphasis id="1042E8887E24757A8AB8BC5508314AE3" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum madagascariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); stamens 10, free, filaments pubescent and eglandular (8-11 mm long in 
<taxonomicName id="E3054E20074E821A624E7B25CD3FFFC7" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum madagascariense" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="madagascariense">
<emphasis id="1584D96DAFAFA83EBD7337800E3700B8" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum madagascariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), anthers dorsifixed, glabrous to pubescent; ovary glabrous. Fruits coriaceous, oblong-elliptic, laterally compressed (but inflated in 
<taxonomicName id="18EA42FEFABC267B37F1F2FCA7BB3223" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum madagascariense" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="madagascariense">
<emphasis id="98D70225C48EF7553420795FC12FD68B" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum madagascariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), glabrous, eglandular pods with a tapering, sharp beak, 18-49 
<normalizedToken id="04BA88B134BA1CF5F015AF02218528A6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-15 mm, elastically dehiscent, with twisting valves. Seeds ovoid, laterally compressed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7A2A2C14A86A8C80F1F24A2CE885C560" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="F8E0A2A689F485B70BC1B89328B2E799" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Geographic distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4FA779597792DC4161CFA944B8B9BE7C" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<taxonomicName id="5ACEFD59E9B0CDABC9577D6E0E9ADD50" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3B6D1EB48B89A32BC9B82DF2039F1A10" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises nine taxa in eight species, found across North America, South America and Africa, including Madagascar, a classical highly disjunct trans-continental distribution typical of lineages occupying the succulent biome sensu 
<bibRefCitation id="1178383CB85682ADF1806982AFC094CF" author="Schrire, BD" editor="Lewis, G" journalOrPublisher="Kew Royal Botanic Gardens, Richmond" pageId="89" pageNumber="90" pagination="21 - 54" refId="B120" refString="Schrire, BD, Lewis, GP, Lavin, M, 2005. Biogeography of the Leguminosae. In: Lewis, G, Schrire, B, Mackinder, B, Lock, M, Eds., Legumes of the World. Kew Royal Botanic Gardens, Richmond: 21 - 54" title="Biogeography of the Leguminosae." volumeTitle="Legumes of the World." year="2005">Schrire et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
. Three species are distributed in Mexico, Florida, and the Caribbean, one species is endemic to Paraguay and Argentina, one is endemic to northern Madagascar, and the other three occur in northern Kenya, Somalia and Arabia. An evaluation of species limits is needed in this group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6094FF04E02E1C2513B7FC1818580538" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="65A82214CA0E304E354B25E1D764B483" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4027A86419A215E4334E65CC8BA92B39" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Low deciduous seasonally dry tropical woodland or scrubland, also in open pineland or coastal plains and foothills. Species in Madagascar and Africa grow in limestone soils.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F1DE441B7AA1FD2AB980CB6946B7BC4B" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9669C916C85E1F704252468D37987D03" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1863E2AFB7FAC1C543A606605012DB2A" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
There is no indication of the etymology of 
<taxonomicName id="DEA9CCF364ADC7B80946164E5E178632" authority="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" authorityName="R.Vig. &amp; Notul.Syst" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Denisophytum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Denisophytum" order="Fabales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="02714FF6DBCC2C2497A619C661386E43" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Denisophytum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the posthumous publication of the generic name. Nevertheless, it is quite likely that the author, 
<normalizedToken id="7709A8D19EE91FA93CC9C1829C023371" originalValue="René">Rene</normalizedToken>
Viguier, had intended to honour his friend and collaborator, Marcel Denis, a botanist with expertise in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="C0A39D5B95A790101185D98A2122359D" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Euphorbia" order="Geraniales" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8DA0A72EB12EE4A9106FBFD1B7ABD479" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Euphorbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Madagascar. Sadly, M. Denis passed away prematurely at the age of 33 in 1929 (
<bibRefCitation id="D2A45836BAEAB04D36EB08A0B3BA45A0" author="Allorge, V" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="693 - 696" publicationUrl="10.1080/00378941.1930.10837216" refId="B1" refString="Allorge, V, Allorge, P, 1930. Marcel Denis (1897-1929). Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France 77 (4): 693 - 696, DOI: 10.1080/00378941.1930.10837216" title="Marcel Denis (1897 - 1929)." url="10.1080/00378941.1930.10837216" volume="77" year="1930">Allorge and Allorge 1930</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
